social_posts.post_text: Let’s talk about what it takes to be good at your trade. I argue that it doesn’t take extra time to go above and beyond and add value to the build process.  Maybe at first it takes time to learn how to learn the technical skills but once you use them more and more, you can probably do something like what you see here in this post almost as fast as it would take to go get a saws all and carve up someone’s else’s work to the point where it needs repair, thus pulling value away from the build process. If you practise your technical skills enough, eventually it’s quicker and second nature to operate at a higher frequency outputting best practises.  This doesn’t go unnoticed. Progression is the profession. Never retire. #construction

Old vs New.  Here stands the very first house I ever touched a truss on and the last house I touched a truss. I was 15 when my old boss and his crew (I wasn’t part of it yet) were roping up trusses on my family home.  I was asked to help carry the trusses on the ground with his apprentice at the time and my dad. The following year during summer break, I got a job on his crew.  I worked for him for 9 years before starting HH&I.  Today, I’m was framing a roof with my crew next door.  I think that’s pretty cool. #construction

Need a place to grow your skills, progress to the next level or looking to become a leader?  Our framing division is looking for people who want to be the industries leaders.  Here at HH&I, we want individuals who value best practices because that’s what our customers demand. We teach the entire build process beyond framing because that’s what makes the best framers. We offer the apprenticeship program to those looking to achieve their RedSeal. We have the best jobs this province has to offer, competitive wages and work life balance.
